  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Ver. 47-49. For a perfect knowledge of all those things which did happen after our Saviour’s nailing to the cross, till he died, and was taken down to be buried, all the evangelists must be consulted. We have made a collection of them in our notes on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Matthew 27:51-56",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 27:51-56",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", to which the reader is here referred. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "See Poole on \"Matthew 27:51\"",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "See Poole on \"",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 27:51",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "\"",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and following verses to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Matthew 27:56",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 27:56",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This passage about the centurion is taken notice of both by Matthew and Mark; only they say he said, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Truly this was the Son of God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Luke saith that he said, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Certainly this was a righteous man.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Possibly the sense is the same, and the centurion by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the Son of",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "God",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " did not mean the Son of God by eternal generation, but one highly favoured of God, a righteous than, and very dear to God, and highly beloved of him; for it must be by a very extraordinary revelation and impression if he, had so early a faith in Christ as God blessed for ever. I think Mr. Calvin, on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Matthew 26:54",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 26:54",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", expounds it well, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Non vulgarem esse hominem, sed divinitus excitatum statuit.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The centurion determined that Christ was no ordinary person, but one stirred up by and sent of God. It is observable, that Christ had a testimony from all orders of men almost, except the scribes, and priests, and Pharisees. Pontius Pilate and Herod declared him innocent. Pilate’s wife acknowledgeth him a righteous person. The thief on the cross testifieth he had ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "done nothing amiss.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Judas the traitor confesseth he had ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "betrayed innocent blood.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The centurion owneth him to be no ordinary man, but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a righteous man, the Son of God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The multitude always owned him: they see they are now run down; they smite their breasts, say nothing, but depart. Only those that were to have been the teachers of others are blinded and hardened to their ruin. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Now when the centurion saw what was done,.... The eclipse of the sun, the darkness upon the land, the earthquake, the rocks rent, and Jesus expire in so uncommon a manner: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "he glorified God; by confessing that Christ was the Son of God, and declaring him an innocent person: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "saying, certainly, this was a righteous man; clear of the charges exhibited against him, and has suffered wrongfully; and this he concluded from those unusual appearances, and which he considered as tokens of divine resentment. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "saying, certainly, this was a righteous man; clear of the charges exhibited against him, and has suffered wrongfully; and this he concluded from those unusual appearances, and which he considered as tokens of divine resentment. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
